description.narrative: By 2022, government and partners at national, state and district level have access to disaggregated data and evidence, with the capacity to use it for prioritizing policy, planning, monitoring and budgetary actions to scale up essential RMNCH+A interventions including demand generation, with focus on marginalized groups, especially the girl child., which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Innovation, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: India&39;s vision and commitment to achieve Universal Health Coverage are reflected in the concerted efforts of UNICEF and partner institutions in programming and implementation of health interventions at disaggregated levels of health systems. UNICEF support to GoI envisages strengthening the community health system in India in line with comprehensive primary health care, especially in aspirational districts. In the light of COVID-19, UNICEF has leveraged digital health technologies to enable intelligent community health systems through real-time monitoring, rollout, and scale-up of ANMOL, technology-driven pilots for evidence-based decision-making interventions, and support in the RCH 2.0 Portal. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:05/01/2022
